animal.description:
Salutations!

I’m Abby, a spunky and KISSY senior chi-terrier mix. My tongue is always flapping for a kiss, partly because I only have 2 teeth left… so it usually is hanging out anyways. My foster mom says there are people out there that love a silly smile and don’t mind ensuring my food is wet and soft.

 My personality is adventurous - I have a LOT of spring in my step for 11 years old. Gotta go somewhere? I wanna go too. I’ve been known to sneak out and hop in the car before anyone has time to pick me up and put me in. Going out at about in the leash and in the car is a favorite pastime. My foster mom cuddles me in her coat and takes me shopping fairly often, and I love to be held close and smell new things. 
I can be timid when I meet new people, but I warm up quick  if there are belly rubs involved. I’ve met other dogs, cats, kids and even a bird with pretty good manners - though I do like to be the center of attention. 

As a senior, I do need to use the ladies pad through out the day. I’ve used potty pads my whole life, and am still getting used to going outside. I think we all appreciate an indoor potty in Michigan weather, right? 

Additional skill sets include cleaning the french fries out of cars, announcing when packages arrive and bringing joy everywhere I go. If you know of anyone interested in a lap dog looking for love, drop a line to www.NBSar.org


These are the things I fur-sure need in my fur-ever home!
- Family who is gone no longer than 5 hour periods.
-Children must be 3yrs or older 
- 100% fenced in yard.
-Diligent about making sure I don't sneak out open doors 

If you think I might be the perfect addition to your family please follow these steps:

1.) Visit www.nbsar.org to fill out my adoption application. As an approved adopter, my rescue friends can set up a home visit so I can meet you. Our rescue is 100% run by volunteers, to help your application be processed as quickly as possible, please make sure to….

2.) Call your veterinarian and give them permission to release information about your current and past pet’s veterinary history.

3.) Call your references too! Let them know to expect a phone call from an unknown phone number, and a rescue team member will need to talk to them on the phone as a reference. 

My adoption fee is $250.00 and includes a DHPP vaccine, bordatella vaccine, de-worming, spay/neuter surgery, rabies vaccine (age appropriate), heartworm test (age appropriate), heartworm preventative, flea/tick preventative, microchip insertion, bath, nail trim, ear cleaning, leash and collar and one week's worth of food. If you’d like to meet me, please apply online and to become an approved adopter! 

Our adoption process requires that any pet in your household be current on vaccinations and heartworm preventative , spayed/neutered (unless a documented medical reason is on file with your veterinarian). Dogs must be current on Distemper DHPP combo vaccine and Rabies vaccine, cats must be current on Distemper and Rabies at the time of application. This also applies to any pets in your home within the past five years.

While I hope that you have fallen in love with me and are ready to apply, I understand if I might not be the perfect pup for your family just yet. However, would you please help by sharing my picture on Facebook, twitter or by email? I'm a great pup and need a loving family to give all of my love and puppy kisses to! Thank-you for your help!
animal.name: Abby

animal.description:
Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.

Sabrina came back to rescue after it was determined she and the other resident dog were not going to work out their differences.  

Her mom says, "Sabrina is a really great little dog, sweet and fun. She loves to go for walks and car rides. She is happy just staying home too if that's where you are. She's about 6 yrs old.   She has never had accidents in the house and does not need a crate. She is used to ringing a little bell next to the door to go outside when needed. She is trustworthy to leave home alone without being destructive. She is half pomeranian and half papillon. Her hair is often kept short in the summer. She is overweight so a diet would be good for her. She has issues with other dogs so she MUST be in an only-dog family. She would be perfect for someone seeking the companionship of a wonderful little pooch who is full of love and craves head and belly rubs. "
 
Please complete and return the adoption application to meet Sabrina, or any of our adoptable dogs.
http://www.route66rescueinc.com/adoption-application.html Thank you for visiting our site. Please come back often.

animal.description:
Hello, I'm Roxanne.  I am a good dog.  I like to play with other dogs and love people.  I am working on improving my manners.  I'm doing well on my school work and trying to learn everything.  If you are needing a good dog like me to have fun times with then I'm available.  If you have a dog who needs a playmate then I'm available.  If you need a good dog like me to teach fun tricks and play games like fetch the ball then I'm a fast learner.   I am the hound type, and I also love to go exploring.  If you need a good explorer to go camping and hiking with then I'm definitely in. 

Opt to Adopt! and give me a chance to love you! Copy/paste this link to your browser to fill out an adoption application for me at: www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org (under the adoption application button).

Once your adoption application is received for me the nice people at Ahimsa Rescue Foundation will set up a convenient time to come meet me.  

Please note:  If you are interested in adopting a pet from Ahimsa Rescue Foundation the first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org     
You will be considered to adopt a pet until an adoption application is received.  

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.


IMPORTANT: If you are interested in adopting a pet from Ahimsa Rescue Foundation the first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at  www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org 
Once your application is received and approved a convenient time will be set with you to meet and adopt a pet.  We hope to see your application soon!

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.

When you "Opt to Adopt" your ADOPTION PACKAGE INCLUDES:
-Pet that has been temperament tested
-Neuter/Spay
-Veterinary General Wellness Exam 
-Vaccinations: Rabies, DHPP, Bordetella
-Blood testing for heartworms, ehrlichiosis, lyme and  A Phagocytophilum disease  
-De-worming for hook, round, whip and tape worms
-Teeth Cleaning if needed 
-New ID Collar, slip leash and ID tags
-Microchip Placement and ID Tag
-Lifetime Registration of your Microchip with Avid microchip company.

There are many wonderful pets who find themselves homeless at no fault of their own.  Thank you considering a rescued companion from all our happy tails and everyone at Ahimsa Rescue Foundation! 

The first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org  To be considered for the adoption of a pet you must submit the on line adoption application.  

We hope to see your application soon.
Ahimsa Rescue Foundation
www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org

AMELIA - ID#A045418
Hi! My name is AMELIA. I am a spayed female, brown and black Plott Hound mix. The shelter staff think I am about 2 years old. I have been at the shelter since Jan 13, 2021.

I LOVE TO: go for walks
I HAVE: been working with the trainer on socialization skills
I GET ALONG WELL WITH: adults and calm children
I WOULD RATHER NOT: be left alone for long periods of time
I NEED: a dog experienced family. I am still a little shy and need a family that is willing to do training with me
I AM: a very sweet girl once I get to know you.

STARTING THE ADOPTION PROCESS:

Thank you for your interest in adopting an animal. To begin the process you will need to access & submit an adoption application. 

You can access our adoption application at either PetProjectFoundation.org or on the City of San Clemente’s website, under the Animal Services option.  
An adoption application can be submitted to the shelter, via Fax at (949) 366-4765, via email to Animalservices@scdpanimalshelter.org, or dropped off at the shelter in the drop box, located by our front door.  The San Clemente – Dana Point Animal Shelter is located at 221 Avenida Fabricante in San Clemente.

We look forward to receiving your application and will be in contact with you via email.

The shelter is currently closed to walk-in public, due to the COVID-19 virus. 

Staff are on site during our regular business hours (below), to address phone calls,  offer shelter services by appointment only, as well as handle any/all animal control concerns.

Our regular business hours are as follows:  
Monday – Closed
Tuesday – 10-4
Wednesday – 10-4
Thursday – 10-4
Friday – 10-4
Saturday – 10-4
Sunday – 12-3
 
In person services are by appointment only, due to the COVID-19 virus, please contact the shelter at (949) 492-1617, for more information.

animal.description:
*This dog is in Texas and will be coming to Ontario the first weekend of February*Please apply to adopt at reddogrescue.org*
This baby and his siblings were born to a mama who got pregnant by another dog because their family did not have the means to get her fixed. They have lived outdoors all of their life and had never received any medical care. They all had ear infections, mange, and worms when Red Dog Rescue found them. The rescue paid for the mom to get spayed and has had each pup treated for their conditions. He would love a home who will be patient and teach him how to be an amazing family dog. With some love and consistency he will flourish into a beautiful and happy pup!
Papa is NOT suitable for first-time dog owners and will require plenty of structure, confidence, and further training to see him transform into a confident dog*
Notes from foster: Papa is such a lovely boy. He is so sweet, but very scared, and when he gets scared he growls. He doesn't share toys or food very well but he loves to run and play. He gets along with everyone here including my son but he is scared to meet new people . It takes him awhile to warm up but when he does he will be your best friend! He loves belly rubs! *Note some pictures are before medical intervention, where is mange can be seen.

Name: Papa
Weight: ~50lb
Age: ~11 months
Gender: Male
Breed: Lab X
Colour: Black with white
Medical: Treated for an ear infection, demodex mange (non-contagious), and hookworms. Papa tested heartworm positive but has received treatment for it.
Fixed: Yes
Good with adults: Yes, however he does not like meeting new people as he is fearful. He takes time to warm up, but is loving once he does. He seems to prefer women.
Good with kids: 12+
Good with dogs: He is dog selective, but does well after proper introductions. Papa grew up within the same pack of dogs and will need further socializing
Good with cats: No
House trained: Working on it!
Crate trained: Working on it!
Food aggressive: Yes, he must be fed alone in his crate
Leash trained: Papa does okay but will need further training
Energy level: Medium-high energy
Suitable for an apartment: No
Can be handled: Yes

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Bobo is an adorable little 7 year-old Chihuahua mix male who found himself homeless at a noisy overcrowded county dog shelter and made the trip to Canine Lifeline so he could relax in a foster home while searching for a permanent new home. This little guy was understandably frightened at the shelter but has warmed up quickly now that he's out of that environment. Bobo loves snuggling with his human friends and gets along well with other dogs too. He even seemed to be fine meeting the resident vet clinic kitty. Bobo has excellent crate manners and may be housetrained too although we can't guarantee it. He is reluctant to walk on a leash at this point but is happy to be carried outside to a fenced area where he immediately takes care of business. Bobo is not a fan of winter weather and loves snuggling up in his cozy blankets once he's back in from the great snowy outdoors. We can't wait to this little guy settling into his very own home! Bobo weighs about 11 pounds and his adoption fee is $325. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. Bobo has had a recent dental cleaning so now flashes a pearly white smile. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Bobo. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Bobo and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

Opt to Adopt! and give me a chance to love you! Copy/paste this link to your browser to fill out an adoption application for me at: www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org (under the adoption application button).

Once your adoption application is received for me the nice people at Ahimsa Rescue Foundation will set up a convenient time to come meet me.

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.


IMPORTANT: If you are interested in adopting a pet from Ahimsa Rescue Foundation the first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at  www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org 
Once your application is received and approved a convenient time will be set with you to meet and adopt a pet.  We hope to see your application soon!

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.

-Pet that has been temperament tested
-Neuter/Spay

-Blood testing for heartworms, ehrlichiosis, lyme and  A Phagocytophilum disease

animal.description:
Name: Priscilla
Breed: Pug
Sex: Female
Age: 7 years
Color: Brindle
Special Characteristics: always smiling, loves to be near her people

Hello pug friends! This lovely lady is Priscilla, a 7 yr. old brindle pug, and she is looking for her forever home! 

Priscilla is a charmer! She is always smiling, she loves to be near her people, and she is as sweet as they come. She is a wonderful companion and is very easy going. She loves her people and also gets along well with her pug foster siblings. 

She never meets a stranger - give her 2 minutes and she will be your BFF. Her foster mom does want to let a potential adopter know that Priscilla's favorite place to sleep at night is near her person's head!! 

Priscilla doesn't like to admit it, but she needs to lose some weight. She is a pug so she loves to beg for treats and give you that cute pug stare, but she needs a person who will really help her shed a few pounds in order to get to a healthy weight and then maintain that weight. She enjoys playing with other dogs and taking walks, so it will be easy to get in some exercise on these nice winter days. 

When Priscilla came into rescue, she had some ear infection issues that we have helped her with. But in true pug fashion, her people will need to clean her ears regularly and keep up with them to make sure no infections return.  

When she joined us, she also had some eye issues that we worked to address quickly.  Because her eyelid openings are quite large, she needs drops to help prevent drying of the corneas. She also has pigmentary keratitis -- this is a condition where the usually clear cornea becomes opaque (this is often due to chronic inflammation). At this time Priscilla receives several eye drops daily and this has helped her a great deal.  She has had a consultation with a specialist and they have suggested she might benefit from eyelid corrective surgery -- basically this would reduce the eyelid opening to hopefully prevent exposure drying of the corneas and eliminate hairs from rubbing on the cornea and help prevent progression of pigmentation.  This surgery would cost a couple thousand dollars.  Because it isn't urgent, we would ideally like to find an adopter for Priscilla who has pug experience and understands this procedure and would help her get this surgery.    

Priscilla is up to date on her vaccines, heartworm negative and spayed. She is perfectly potty trained and a delightful housemate. 

We are looking for a special rescue family for this girl -- her ideal home should have someone home a lot, previous pug experience so they understand her ongoing eye issues, and another pug playmate.

If you think Priscilla would be a great addition to your family, please complete an adoption application today at https://pugrescueofflorida.org/adopt

If you love me but can't adopt me please consider making a donation to rescue to help pay medical bills for not just me but my fellow foster brothers and sisters.

My Rescue friends are working very hard to find me and the other foster pugs new homes, so please be sure to submit an application before contacting them.

More information and  applications are available at WWW.PUGRESCUEOFFLORIDA.ORG

ANNIE - ID#A045421
Hi! My name is ANNIE. I am a spayed female, white and black English Bulldog and American Bulldog. The shelter staff think I am about 3 years old. I have been at the shelter since Jan 13, 2021.

I LOVE TO: run around and play in the yard
I HAVE: a very happy, friendly personality.
I GET ALONG WELL WITH: families with children
I WOULD RATHER NOT: be left alone for long periods of time.
I NEED: some basic training skills
I AM: a very active dog

STARTING THE ADOPTION PROCESS:

Thank you for your interest in adopting an animal. To begin the process you will need to access & submit an adoption application. 

You can access our adoption application at either PetProjectFoundation.org or on the City of San Clemente’s website, under the Animal Services option.  
An adoption application can be submitted to the shelter, via Fax at (949) 366-4765, via email to Animalservices@scdpanimalshelter.org, or dropped off at the shelter in the drop box, located by our front door.  The San Clemente – Dana Point Animal Shelter is located at 221 Avenida Fabricante in San Clemente.

We look forward to receiving your application and will be in contact with you via email.

The shelter is currently closed to walk-in public, due to the COVID-19 virus. 

Staff are on site during our regular business hours (below), to address phone calls,  offer shelter services by appointment only, as well as handle any/all animal control concerns.

Our regular business hours are as follows:  
Monday – Closed
Tuesday – 10-4
Wednesday – 10-4
Thursday – 10-4
Friday – 10-4
Saturday – 10-4
Sunday – 12-3
 
In person services are by appointment only, due to the COVID-19 virus, please contact the shelter at (949) 492-1617, for more information.

animal.description:
Meet Ozzy, a six year old, approximately 40lb heeler mix that is needing to find a new home due to some really hard circumstances.  Ozzy has lived with his mom and dad for five years.  They found out that they are expecting a child in a few months.  Due to Ozzy not being good with children, they are making one of the toughest decisions in their lives.  They love him so much that they are looking to find him his forever family.  Ozzy will do great in any home that  has no children under 16.  He also loves all other dogs and would do best as a second dog.  He does live as the only dog right now but does get stressed in storms which can bring anxiety.  If you are looking for a very calm couch potato or a nice walking partner please come meet Ozzy. He is potty trained and knows several commands. His mom and dad really want to make sure he is going to the best home possible for him.  You will not find a calmer easier dog to have as your family member.

If you are interested in Ozzy, please fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

animal.description:
My name is Maggie and I am an 8 month young Red Heeler. I was left in a cage in a field in TN and that is how I was found.  Luckily I wasn't there for too long.  I hated being caged up in such a nice field. Caged in a field?!?  A Heeler needs to run in that field not be caged!  

I am extremely smart and very high energy.  That is just my breed but I am smarter and faster than most!  My new family will understand my level of energy and they will keep up with me.  I really like it here in my foster home where I have another doggie that I can play with all day in the back yard.  My foster mom says that I must have a backyard where I can play and get all my energy out.  She said that I am so smart that I could be an agility dog.  What is that? I must find out! 

I like kids and tolerate cats and I am already a lady since I know to go outside to do my business like a proper lady should.  I also figured out how to walk on leash without dragging you all over the place. (even though I could easily do so) 
I am also crate trained and I am quiet all night.  I told you I am a lady, did you not listen? 

I love to play. I can play all day but when I am done I like to cuddle with my human friends. 

My foster mom says that I am a beautiful girl, smart and lovely and that my forever family will be very lucky to adopt me.  Do you think so? 

I can't wait to meet you.  I will put a smile on your face every day of my life and I will warm your heart at night. While I patiently wait for you, I will learn this agility thing my foster mom talks about! I can climb, jump and listen to commands. What else can a girl like me do?  Let me show ya!
Until then

Love
Maggie.

Maggie is located in our foster home in Chicago/Avondale area.  To meet this cutie, please complete an adoption application at:  https://treasuredanimalrescueinc.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
A FUN, FROLICKING FRIEND:  1 year old / 22 lbs. 

Hi there!  My name is Janine! I came to Mostly Mutts from animal control and am so happy to be on my journey to finding a furever home with my new and wonderful family!  

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I haven’t met other dogs at Mostly Mutts yet though I am a playful dog, so if you have a doggie who is also a fan of playing, let’s meet and see if we can do that together / Cats unknown / I also haven’t met kids yet at Mostly Mutts, so let’s meet and best no toddlers or small children that I may bump over, and I am currently super mouthy when I play.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am a happy gal who is a typical bundle of young dog energy.  Playful, fun and affectionate, I am alert and seem to have good focus – ready to learn all I need to know to be a great friend / My energy level is 8-10 which is very high, so plan to be active with me daily! 

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I am now a student in the Mostly Mutts University training program, where I’ll be learning lots of great doggie commands with my trainer.  I’ve already mastered ‘sit’ and ‘down’.  I’m also working on my leash manners (I jump and weave on my leash right now but am improving).  I love treats so this will make my training fun and rewarding for both of us / My crate manners are good at Mostly Mutts / I’ve had good potty habits on the shelter schedule, so hopefully that will be the case in my new home.         

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I like to play and enjoy being silly with the volunteers in the play yard at the shelter, so I bet I would enjoy running around in a fenced yard with you.  I love Nyla bones and toys and I like holding one to keep my mouth busy while you harness me for a walk / I can’t think of any dislikes, but I would not be a happy pup if I did not get much needed exercise, training and love.   

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed.

I am looking for a family that will be very active with me!  A fun family to make lots of good memories with!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description: Penny is a sweet, senior girl who came to PACC with some senior girl issues. The shelter is no place for a 15-year-old girl to spend her time. She enjoys treats (especially cheese) and taking in the sights and sounds on her walks. Penny enjoys being petted and close to people, and she really needs to get out of the shelter and into the home. If you've got a soft place in your home for a sweet girl like Penny, make an appointment to meet her today.

animal.description:
A LOVING & GENTLE FRIEND:  6 – 7 months old / Currently 40 lbs.

Hello!  My name is Jordan!  I came to Mostly Mutts from animal control – sweet, loving and ready to find my furever family!  I came in with some hair loss on my head and body, and medicated baths are helping with that. 

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I like the dog in my foster home and try to engage her in play.  She is older and not interested in playing with me, but I bet I would like another dog in my new home who is looking for a playmate, so let’s meet / Cats unknown / I haven’t met kids yet at Mostly Mutts, but my foster thinks my temperament might be a good fit for kids, but best no toddlers that I may bump over and let’s meet.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am very sweet and affectionate – a people dog!  I can be a bit timid at first in new environments, where new or strange noises can make me run and hide or show my belly in submission.  Please make sure I do not slip out the door and get lost if I hear something that startles me inside or outside.  I am generally quiet but will whimper a little when my favorite person (my foster dad) leaves the room.  I charmed the MM photographer and – don’t tell anyone, but she said I may be her favorite – lol / My energy level is around a 4-6.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I know the ‘sit’ command, and my foster family is working on ‘down’ and ‘place’ with me.  I bet you can teach me even more great doggie commands.  I have good leash manners, though I am frightened of the leash itself, so I tend to hide from it.  I have learned to sit now for you to put it on, though I may be afraid of it for a while in my new home / I do well in a crate, though I’ve not been crated much in my foster home.  I sleep through the night on a comfy doggie bed in my fosters’ room / My potty habits have been good in my foster home, so hopefully that will be the case in my new home too.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I like spending time with my people and getting lots of belly rubs – my favorite.  I am happy when I am giving or receiving affection.  I enjoy my food also and may even be a bit obsessed with it - lol / Other than the sight of the leash and strange noises that startle me, I can’t think of any dislikes, though I would not be happy if I did not get the love and attention on which I thrive.

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and neutered.  I formerly had non-contagious mange, so I’m on a chewable tablet twice a month through February.  I may need special baths for a little while longer which can be done in my new home.  

If you are looking to add a charming fur friend to your family, I may be your guy!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
Introducing this amazing duo, the owner of many of our hearts, Wilma and Wilton!! When we say we are in love with them, words cannot really do justice. Their story broke our hearts and we have cherished them since the moment we laid eyes on them! We rescued them the day after they were born. They come from a trailer park in a very destitute place. Their mom had lived there since as far back as the folks there could remember, but she was not treated kindly. Her owners didn’t feed, water or provide adequate shelter for her. She would sleep in a bed of nails and insulation outside under a trailer. According to the people we spoke with, she was obviously pregnant. Someone nearby went looking when they didn’t see her that day and found her at night, having just given birth, in her dirty fiberglass nest she made... she was desperately trying to keep her babies warm and it was only about 20 degrees outside. After finding them she tried everything to get someone to save them that day. Our volunteer wasn’t close by but eventually word got to her the next day and she went ASAP to save them. Upon arrival was devastating heartbreak. Without going into graphic detail, we will say the only survivors were Wilma and Wilton. They were taken, along with their mom, and finally got the love and care they deserved.
Their mom was in an extremely poor physical state due to severe neglect and sleeping in fiberglass, but she did everything she could to raise these two. Their mom has the most incredible heart of gold you could have imagined. The story of Wilma and Wilton, and their amazing mother, will live within us always. 
It is now that we are delighted to present these two remarkable survivors!! These two healthy, strong, gorgeous, wonderful, sweet babies, Wilma and Wilton!! They are a bonded pair and we are committed to placing them together. They love each other so much, and after their start in life we cannot imagine ever separating them! Wilma looks JUST like her mama!! And she is a strong and a brilliant old soul, just like her! She is the more confident of the two and you can tell she is destined for greatness! Wilton is a glorious mushball who follows Wanda’s every move and adores her! They are an amazing dynamic duo and not only adore playing and snuggling with each other, but they loooove people!! If you snuggle on the couch with them they will start out by giving you hundreds of kisses and nibbles!! They are MASTER snugglers!!! Soooo super adorable and in love with their people!! They are so remarkable and we are determined to find parents for them who are just as remarkable! They need parents who reflect them:) super loving, affectionate, sweet, strong and confident! They need parents who LOVE to snuggle with their pups and will be committed to them as family members! They would love a big yard to run and play with and parents who would love to bring them in car rides and treat them as their kids! These babies are amazing and we cannot wait to see their dreams come true!! If you would love to be the lucky person to welcome these two amazing babies to your family, please visit our website and submit an application for adoption today!! www.greatdivideanimalrescue.org

animal.description:
Hi Future Family! 

I'm Matilda and I'm looking for my own very own Miss Honey! I'm a sweet and energetic pup - here are some things about me!

Favorite things:
Attention! Give me attention and I'm a happy, happy girl!
Sniffs! I love all the smells and my nose does not stop! That also means that I might get so caught up on a smell and travel farther than I realize - a harness/leash and  fence is important to keep me safe!
Playing! I love to play with my doggie foster brother! It wears me out..
Toys! it's important that I have appropriate toys to chew on so that I don't chew on your favorite things. If I have the right toys, I'm good to go!
Relaxing and recharging on a dog bed! I play hard and then I rest hard - it's that simple!
Humans: Humans are the best! I'm learning that I can get pets without jumping, but I need some work on that! My foster family doesn't have little humans so they aren't sure how I'll do, but because of my jumping, I'll probably do best with older children.

Other dogs: Before I came to Minnesota, I had puppies that I was responsible for protecting. I still think it's my job to be protective and I'm slow to warm up to dogs. Once I'm comfortable, I LOVE to play. Did I mention that I really love my fur foster brother? I'd probably like a doggie sibling, but I will absolutely need a slow and patient introduction. I did struggle to share our bed and toys so I need a doggie sibling that reads my cues and is flexible with sharing while we work on this together. I think this could get easier for me! My foster mom and dad say that I can trust them to let me know which dogs are friends and to make sure I have everything I need - I don't need to act so tough or be protective of my stuff. They said when I join your family, you'll do the same for me.. but it will take a little time for me to learn that you've got my back!

Leash training: I LOVE walks! I'm so excited that I do pull on a leash and I need some work on that. I really think I might like to be your running or hiking buddy!

Crate training: So far, so good! I get a little sad and I do protest when you leave me, but if I've had enough exercise, I'll just snooze away until you come back! I sleep in my crate at night in the same room as my foster family. It's great!

House training: I'm super close to being house trained! I've had a couple accidents, but my foster mom says that can happen after big changes. I’m also starting to communicate when I need to go outside! Also, where is all your grass?! Thankfully the snow doesn't bother me, but it was confusing at first!

Commands: I'm learning sit, come, leave it. I'm motivated by treats and I think I can learn quickly! I will just need continued and consistent training. If you work hard, I'll work hard! I promise!

I’m really looking for a loving family that will give me attention, likes to help me exercise, and is willing to work on my training!
If you would like to meet Matilda, please visits spotslaststop.org and fill out an application.

animal.description:
**COURTESY POST FOR OWNER**

Owner's note about Phish:
 
"Her name is Phish and she is honestly the sweetest and smartest dog I have ever known. She loves to cuddle and give lots of kisses. She is great with people, warms up to strangers fast, and is good with kids. She is a great hiking and running partner. She loves to wear clothes and snuggle up in blankets. She knows commands like sit, wait, come, quiet, off, and place. She is a pit bull terrier mix. Black and white. About two years old and up to date on all of her shots/vaccinations. She is spayed. 
 
Despite all of these wonderful qualities she does have a problem with other dogs. I did not know that she was dog aggressive when I got her but found out after the fact. Over the weekend she got into a serious fight with my mom's dog. They had met many times before and had been together all day with no issues. Both dogs are okay, Phish only has minor lacerations around her face. The other dog has more severe injuries but is doing just fine. 
 
If I were living alone or if she was the only dog I would keep her for sure. However, my sister has a dog and after a lot of discussions between her and Phish's trainer I came to the decision that it would be best to find her a new home where she can be the only dog."

Please fill out our adoption application and we will forward it to Phish's owner for them to contact you. https://2ndchance.rescuegroups.org/animals/detail?AnimalID=16470780

animal.description:
*please read entire bio before applying*

Hi everyone, I’m Max! I’m new in town and am pretty skittish with all these new places and smells. But once I settle in, I’m mostly a homebody and enjoy being around my people (I sometimes whine when I can’t see my favorite people, but not for too long!). I’m good about sleeping in my crate at night and am fully potty trained! I’m a little 10 lb couch potato that doesn’t like being left alone. I am also not a fan of loud noises (we’re all scared of something). I’ve been called an escape artist so a close eye in the yard would be a great thing for me. Mostly I love to snuggle on my people’s laps and soak up some attention. I am not a fan of cats, but big dogs I get along with. In my short time here, I’ve only been around older kids and adults but am open to meeting some littles, at my own pace of course.

Do you think I would be a good fit for your home? Apply for me at www.lucky7dogrescue.com/applynow

Franky

Breed: Chihuahua mix
Housetrained: Yes
Good with cats: Unknown
Good with other dogs: May do well with a calm dog companion
Good with children: No
Preferred home environment: Securely fenced-in yard
Intake date/origin: January 2021, surrendered by owner
Vetting: Already neutered, microchipped, and UTD on vaccines including rabies
Adoption fee: $150

Meet Franky. Born in January 2019, this boy arrived in our care when his owner developed health complications and could no longer care for him.

Franky is very shy. So far, he has not shown us much of his personality. He will need a patient owner who will take things slow with him and help him come out of his shell. Franky needs a securely fenced-in yard. He should not live in a home with children, although he may do well with a calm dog friend. Franky is housetrained.

Will you provide Franky with a loving place to call home? Apply to adopt him at www.lovingheartanimalshelter.org/adopt.

animal.description:
"Howdy! Have you ever seen a dog as adorable as me?! Can you believe I’m homeless and am waiting for a wonderful person or family to adopt me? Great dogs like me end up in animal shelters every day- I know, it’s so hard to believe but it’s true!

My name is Jax, and I just joined the adoptable doggy crew at Providence Animal Center from North Carolina. I'm around 7 years old, about 17 pounds, and I'm all set to move right into your heart & home today - already neutered, microchipped & up to date on vaccinations. 

I'm currently staying with a foster family and enjoying the company of my foster siblings. They are helping me build my confidence. I would love a home with another doggy roommate. My ideal home would have a fenced in yard as I have not had a lot of exposure to the world, so I'm a bit apprehensive of it, so a suburban home might would suit me best. I'm hoping to work on my leash skills without lots of distractions. If you have children in the home, I would do best with older children that are about 15 years old or older.

My foster mom has the following to say about me:
"Jax is a super sweet dog. He loves his naps. He was nervous in the beginning but once he knows he is safe, he settled right in. He is very food motivated. His leash skills are progressing. The harness really helps! He has also done well with our cat!"

The staff would love to match you with your new best friend forever - and hopefully that's me! If you are interested in me, please complete an adoption profile (found here: https://providenceac.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Adoption-Profile.pdf) and email it to my friends at foster@providenceac.org. I can't wait to hear from you! XOXO Jax"

animal.description:
Scrappy is a very special senior boy. He is about 11 years old. He was surrendered to the shelter due to some unknown medical issues. Our vet determined that he had oral cancer. He has recently undergone surgeries at a specialty vet hospital to remove part of his lower jaw to remove the cancer. They believe that he has a very good prognosis for a healthy life moving forward based on the surgeon’s assessment and his pathology report. He has an eight week follow up appointment scheduled in early March and has been healing nicely. He eats and drinks very well, though his tongue does stick out and he does drool a lot. He is a messy eater due to missing some of his lower jaw, and requires a little help getting cleaned up after meals. 

We very lovingly refer to Scrappy as our grumpy old man. He is very grumbly and vocal, but he does warm up eventually and loves to be part of the pack. He’s currently living in a foster home with two small older dogs and a toddler and he is doing well getting along with everyone. He enjoys spending time out in the yard and likes riding in the car and going for walks. 

Being a standard dachshund, he does struggle with multiple stairs and needs to be carried up and down. He is able to hop up and down one or two steps. His current diet consists of wet canned prescription food (Hill’s I/D or Purina EN). This has been prescribed in order to meet his mouth care needs and also to alleviate some digestion and gastrointestinal issues he was having. He has done much better on the prescription food and hasn’t had any further issues since starting on the prescription food. 

Scrappy will need an adoptive family who will be patient with him and his needs and who will take their time letting him slowly settle in.

animal.description:
Active, playful & sweet, everyone meet our beautiful baby girl Nova. She's a 10 month old Belgian Shepherd (Malinois)/ Doberman mix who weighs in around 50lbs. Nova loves to play tag with other dogs & is good at sharing her toys, but not interested in sharing her food or her kennel space. She can be shy at first, but will definitely warm up after playing some tug of war! Nova's sweet loving eyes, floppy ears & her curled tail are her foster parents favorite things about her. Nova is very affectionate & loves to give kisses that’s how she tricks you into playing with her non stop! She's 100% potty trained, 100% crate trained and is getting better on a leash. Nova does great with other dogs, great with older kids due to her energy level & curious about cats.

Adoption #Requirements: No Exceptions

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. Copy and paste the link to access the sign-up genius for an appointment: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet for dogs and https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1 for cats.

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Good with other dogs at shelter


Adoption Coordinator: Center staff
Location: Adoption Center

The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. animal.description:
*please read entire bio before applying*

Hi, I’m Toronto. I’m 7 years old, and quite the special guy. My vision and hearing are impaired, but that doesn’t mean I am not awesome.. I learn my way around a new space fairly quickly- but I am requesting a home with older children (if any) and no staircases unless they are securely barricaded. Safety first... and treats second, please! I love my snacks. I am not much for playtime, but I live with other little doggies and kitties. We get along just fine. 

I get a little jumpy, so approaching me slowly is much appreciated. I am a quiet guy, but I do enjoy my peoples’ company- so if I am alone for an extended period, you may hear about it. Cuddling on your lap isn’t really my forte, but in a relaxed environment I will certainly plop down next to you.

It’s hard for me to navigate doors, so housetraining may require the use of pads in a regular location. Patience and routine guided trips to the area would be most helpful. I would love to be the chill buddy in your quiet home. If you think you would be a good fit apply at www.lucky7dogrescue.com/applynow

animal.description:
*please read entire bio before applying*

Hey there, I’m Delilah, and I have no idea what it’s like in New York City… In fact I come from Texas and am not enjoying this cold weather in Wisconsin. Frankly, nobody should be surprised considering I lived the first 8 years of my life in the south and only weigh 10 pounds. I am still getting used to a lot of things up here in the north. I am not a fan of my collar and try to slip out of it, leashes are the scariest thing I have ever seen, and please don’t pick me up unless it’s necessary. I am a dignified, independent lady. I spend my days perched on the couch watching everything and will give you love on my terms. Speaking of love - I am a huge fan of other dogs. I would love to have a sibling to play with and keep me company. I also really like spending time with my foster family. I let them know how much I miss them when I can’t see them by howling my sorrows. As my foster family says, I am the perfect companion for having a glass of wine and reading. I may not be able to actually read with you as my sight and hearing are not as good as they used to be, but I am super chill and will love being with you. I just need a little time to adjust to all these changes. Would you be willing to give this experienced lady a second chance? I promise to love you forever. If you think you can provide me with a safe and patient home, please apply at https://www.lucky7dogrescue.com/adoptabledogs

animal.description:
Meet Darcy, an approximately 9 week old hound mix who became a Misfit when she and her siblings were put in a cat food bag and tossed out like trash when they were newborns (they still had their umbilical cords). This pet is  , up to date on all age-appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, heart-worm negative, and micro-chipped! 

Darcy is a happy go lucky gal that loves her dog companions as much as she loves her human companions. Darcy does like to nap, but she still gets the zoomies like any young puppy does! Her foster mom did a dog DNA test and discovered she is mostly Blue Tick Coonhound, but she also has equal parts Australian Cattle Dog, Corgi, and Weimaraner. These are all active breeds and for that reason, Darcy will do best with an active family that will take her on adventures – she would love to be a hiking or running buddy. 

Darcy lives with all of her littermates, as well as two other puppies and several big dogs. She also lives with two cats in here foster home. She has done great with everyone. So far, she has very little interest in the cats and loves to play with the dogs, but she’s also really good at entertaining herself with dog toys and running laps around the backyard. Darcy hasn’t been around kids, but her foster mom doesn’t have any concern with her being with kids. Like any puppy, she may have to be taught appropriate boundaries with kids, but she is a gentle girl that takes direction extremely well. 

Sometimes Darcy will sit and watch her foster mom almost as if she is waiting for direction. For this reason, her foster mom believes she is extremely intelligent and will be a super easy dog to train. She has started going outside, but will need work on potty training and kennel training. She stays in a penduring the day and at night with her littermates, so when she is adopted, she will need a little time to adjust to being on her own; it will be a big change for her. 

You can apply to meet / adopt this pet at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
MOONBEAM (female, black and white) and SILVER (male, shiny grey coat) are beautiful young lab mix siblings found abandoned in a campground. Thankfully, Moonbeam and Silver were found by caring forestry workers who fostered them for a week until they found rescue for them.

Moonbeam (36 lbs) and Silver (42 lbs) are lab mixes. Silver looks as if he may have some Weimaraner in him. They are young, maybe a year old. They love to do labby things -- play ball, frisbee and tug, find sticks and try to catch moles and chipmunks. They appear to be housebroken and know basic commands. Moonbeam is very outgoing, Silver is more cautious upon first meeting, but yummy treats win him over. They seem to warm up to men more quickly. If we can't find a home where they can stay together, we will send them to separate homes. Silver definitely requires the companionship of another dog. Moonbeam might be okay as an only dog. dreamhouserescue.org.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Winnie was owner surrendered to Pet Rescue by Judy. This breed is known for being protective, capable, fearless, and determined. On the other hand, these dogs are also described as docile, friendly, and affectionate. They are not at all aggressive or aloof- quite the contrary. Keep in mind that these dogs like to chew a lot, so you should give your pooch a variety of bones and toys that are safe to chew. Giving your pet plenty of toys to play with while spending time indoors will also keep him mentally stimulated so boredom won't lead to unwanted behaviors. Winnie is housebroke and crate trained, she is good with other dogs and cats. At this time because she just came to us and and we are unfamiliar with her behavior towards children, people, eating, playing. Once she is evaluated further we will update her web page accordingly. We were told from her previous owner that he felt Winnie might have been abused at one time in her life. She does not like broom sticks or any kind of stick. Two of the family members in the home were male, tall and skinny, Winnie did not respond well to them. We will evaluate this. She is scared of fireworks, skate boards. She is good with women.
Right now she is fitting in great with all the people coming in and out at the rescue and all the dogs barking. Sh seems very quiet.

animal.description:
I'm a pretty shy fella, coming from a home with nearly 200 dogs, I haven't really been exposed to a lot of people or love. In the last three weeks, I've had a lot of firsts:


	first time outside
	first time on a leash
	first time on a walk
	first time bathrooming outside
	first time watching a video conference with intense fascination 


It's been a lot of new stuff to learn, but I'm told I'm progressing really well. I love dogs of all sizes and I'm learning how to play, but am still learning to be calm around humans of all sizes. When I see a new one, I want to run away and hide. Always flight, no fight.

I'm comfortable laying on a dog bed on the floor next to my foster parents and following them around the house, but I'm not ready to be pet or cuddled. I've taken to potty training really well, but I still need some potty pads in the home while I'm leash training. I'm looking for a real special adopter who can exercise a lot of patience, understanding, and training, cause my rehab will take some time, but I'll give you lots of smiles and nose pokes while we're working on it together. 

I like collecting fluff toys and nomming on antlers. I love peanut butter and rolling around in the fresh snow. I think I'd be most comfortable somewhere with a fence to play freely and a confident dog friend to learn from.

animal.description:
B-I-N-G-O. B-I-N-G-O. B-I-N-G-O and Bingo was his nameo! 
Bingo will have you singing with joy from all of the love and affection he gives. Bingo is a people type of person-I mean dog- who just wants to be with his furever family! In his previous home he lived both indoors and outdoors and was completely potty trained, he loves to play with rubber balls, and is a PRO at playing fetch. This young boy may be rambunctious and playful but he's also booksmart and knows the verbal cues "sit", "come" and "stay"! While Bingo has been around children before, and he LOVED THEM, he plays very rough. If you have children in the home, keep in mind what their comfort level is with dogs. Bingo would LOVE to meet them here first before coming home with you!

Bingo is a boy of refine taste, and if there are any other pets in the home would prefer that they are around his size or larger. If you do have another large dog he asks that you bring them for a doggie date to make sure they are compatible before adopting! 

Come meet Bingo at KCCAC today

animal.description: Hey guys, my name is Misty! I am a 2.5 year old, mutt looking for a new home! I am currently 45 pounds and have sadly been in two crowded southern shelters just waiting for my perfect family. Luckily, when my time was near, the Humane Society scooped me up and brought me here until I could find the best home possible! So far, I have showed how spunky and fun I am. I have played well with dogs both small and large and did wonderfully! I will be cat tested soon. As for children, the shelter staff believe I will be best with sturdy kids. My zoomies could easily knock over a child. I would also do best in a house rather than an apartment. My energy is fun and booming, so keep that in mind when adopting me. I am very friendly and love going for walks. If you are looking for a hiking buddy, I would be perfect too! if you would like to add me to your home, please fill out an application and schedule a time to come meet me!

I look forward to meeting you very soon.

**If you're interested in learning more about River, please email Paula.rayman@lostdogrescue.org**

"You can't be unhappy in the middle of a big, beautiful river. -Jim Harrison
 
And you can't be unhappy in the company of this big, beautiful River. This friendly giant loves people and is excited about life. River knows some commands (such as "sit) and responds well to leash steering. He is also crate- and house-trained. River loves treats, and he should be a quick learner. 
 
River's ideal family is someone who can handle his enviable muscles, as River is a strong boy. He would do best in a home without small children, other dogs, or senior adults for this same reason.
 
There is no better way to start 2021 than with River. His zest for life and love will bring joy to a lucky family.

Sponsored by Brian McNeill

animal.description:
Charlie is an older gentleman with a sweet, calm demeanor!

Easy Going! Charlie isn’t the type of guy who gets too worked up about anything. He’s relaxed in most settings, although he can be a little hesitant around new people. Charlie is calm and patient around new dogs and likes to play once he makes a friend!

Well-Mannered! Charlie is truly a gentleman! He’s great on a leash – although if he needs to stop for a potty break, he may pull a little. Charlie is well behaved when home alone – his foster has never needed to put him in a crate. Miss Manners herself would have few critiques for this guy!

Sweet as sugar! Charlie’s favorite activity? Being loved on! He’s an affectionate guy who is happy to be wherever you are. His second favorite activity? Running. But only if you’re there, he’ll love you too much too run away!

Charlie is everything you want in a gentleman, and you’re everything he wants in a human!

animal.description:
Hi there!!! My name is Oahu, an 8½ week old female Pomeranian mix.  My life, along with some of my siblings, started out a bit rough but on the right track for an awesome life.  I love playing with my siblings and the other dogs in my foster home are pretty cool too.  My foster humans are showing me the snuggles are one of the greatest things besides those things they call toys.  I'm ready to get moving on to my wonderful loving life.  

I will come with the works (Neutered/Spayed, up to date on everything, micro chipped, fecal, heartworm tested if age appropriate, heartworm, flea and tick preventative, one month insurance and free vet visit).  What more could a new family ask for?  COVID 19 restrictions:  If I have not been altered by adoption I will have to return to my vet for my procedure.

If you are interested in meeting and thinking about adoption, please visit our website http//www.wagginghearts.org and submit an adoption application. Include the name(s) of the animal(s) you are interested in the subject line of the email. Due to the high volume of applications we receive we are only able to process fully completed applications. We do not reply to inquiries. Since we are a foster based rescue we are unable to set up meet and greets until a completed application is on file and has been approved. 

Wagging Hearts is a 100% foster-based, non-profit rescue organization. 

Our mission is to rescue abandoned, neglected, and stray companion animals. Please visit http//www.wagginghearts.org if you would like to adopt and provide a forever home to one in need.

animal.description:
There are dozens of words for snow, and Snirt might be one of the cutest ones. This Aussie mix puppy is a tiny little guy with a playful personality. Hes interested in everything going on around him and can be independent, going off on the occasional bold adventure. Then hell cuddle with his people, play with his brother or the big dogs (all the other dogs seem HUGE when youre this size), and settle in for a nap.

Snirt is hearing and vision impaired so hes learning touch commands to navigate his world. Right now, that means lots of playing, eating, and running through his tunnel with his favorite ball. But the very best play time is wrestling and chewing on toys. Hed love a home with a fenced-in yard for safe adventures where an active family will keep things fun. It would be great if theres another dog for playing because Snirt adores all animals.

Hed love a home with a fenced-in yard for safe adventures where an active family will keep things fun. It would be great if theres another dog for playing because Snirt adores all animals. Snirt is up to date on vaccinations, neutered, microchipped, and current on heartworm/flea and tick prevention. Also included in his adoption is a Fi GPS collar and one year of GPS service subscription. If he were to escape, as soon as he leaves the safe zone you set around your home, you are alerted so that you can find Snirt's whereabouts. Youll also be able to see how many steps per day he takes to ensure he gets the right amount of exercise, alongside many other features to explore in the Fi mobile app.

animal.description: Kila is ready to be your Valentine! This beautiful girl is a sweetie who is ready to give all her love to someone special. Abandoned in a home when her family moved away, she was confused and heartbroken, making her transition at Sarasota County Animal Services very difficult. Kila was very scared and did not show her true personality well so SCAS reached out to Satchel's for help. Kila can be timid at first but food is the key to her heart. She seems to be okay with both cats and other dogs. Give her a chance and she is sure to melt your heart. Kila is estimated to be 2 years old and weighs approximately 50 lbs.

animal.description:
Hello, I'm Zelda. I'm a lovable chocolate pit mix, and I love to adventure and explore! I've got a purple dot because I can be very protective over my food and treats, so I need to be in a home with an experienced dog owner, and no children, please! My friends here at HSSC have been working very hard with me to correct this behavior, and I'm now able to trade food and possessions for treats, but I will need to go home with someone who understands my behavior and is committed to continuing my training at home so that I don't revert. I can be a little picky with treats, but so far my favorite is cheese! I'm not too interested in toys, I'd much rather go for a long walk followed by a nap on the couch. If you're an active person and you understand my behavior, please come to see me! Maybe you'll fall in love!

What's HW+? I'm currently being treated for heartworms. I'll need to keep a calm lifestyle until finished and may require an appointment or two. Please don't be deterred, my lifespan isn't shortened, and I'm not contagious to your other pets.

Take me on a Slumber Party! You can bring me home for a 3 day - 30 day trial period. HSSC will provide food, medications, and necessities. If I'm not the one for you, just bring me back to HSSC and provide feedback on what would be the best home for me.

1/29/2021 - My name is Jovi

Jovi: Estimated DOB: 1/29/2018, English Setter mix, female, 50 pounds, house trained, crate trained, Good with cats, Good with kids   ** Special needs**
 
Jovi is a sweet girl searching for the perfect family! She is super affectionate and loves receiving attention. She likes being with her people and is very social. Jovi makes friends with everyone including dogs, cats, birds, and children. Jovi LOVES to run! She would love a large back yard to call her own. Jovi would do best with a privacy fence that she can not see through. Jovi is well mannered around the house. She is house trained and will bark to let you know she is ready to go out.
 
Jovi is a special needs pup. She was born deaf. She does know show basic hands signs. Jovi was later hit by a car because she was unable to hear it coming. She broke her pelvis at that time and had to undergo a surgery. She has fully healed but will always walk with a limp.

* The adoption fee of $425 includes age-appropriate vaccines, initial de-worming, spay/neuter surgery, microchip and transport fee.

animal.description: Nikki is a 3 year old pug mix that came to PugHearts from a shelter in The Valley. We believe Nikki is a Pug-Beagle Mix, better known as a Puggle. Unfortunately Nikki came in to rescue already pregnant too. On Christmas Eve she gave birth to 5 healthy puppies. Nikki is the most loving little girl. She loves belly rubs, chew toys and sunning on the patio. She gets along great with her foster siblings, and is great with children too. She has impeccable house manners and hardly barks. Nikki won’t be ready for adoption until she can be spayed, which will be about 12 weeks after delivery. She is such a good mommy to her babies that were all named for the cold day they were born on. Stay tuned! Introductions will be soon for Paloma, Lumi, Neve, Cole and Crystal.

animal.description:
Life has not been kind to sweet Zoe but that is all about to change.  She’s the perfect example of why no one should adopt a dog on a whim.  Zoe was purchased as a small puppy but her family soon grew tired of her.  They left her alone outside in the backyard and seldom paid any attention to her.  She never went to the vet and sometimes they neglected to feed her.  In fact, she didn’t even have a name!  Fortunately, Zoe had a special friend that was watching over her.  Fate stepped in and she was able to convince Zoe’s family to surrender her to our care.  Her rescuer told us she named her “Zoe” because it means “life”; the wonderful new life this special dog deserved in the arms of a loving family.
Zoe is a two and half year old Siberian Husky and absolutely stunning!  She can be shy at first because she is not used to meeting new people.  Once you gain her trust, she’s quite loving and friendly.  A large playful pup, she is so starved for affection and attention.  She weighs fifty-seven pounds and sometimes can knock you over with her enthusiastic love.  Zoe means no harm but could be too much for little children or seniors.  She needs someone that enjoys an active lifestyle and can handle a large strong dog.  Zoe needs plenty of exercise including daily walks or long runs.  She is working on her leash skills and learning not to pull.  
Zoe will make a wonderful companion but is a little rough around the edges.  With a little patience and time, Zoe will quickly learn to curb her enthusiasm.  She is exceptionally smart and eager to please.  She will learn new obedience skills quickly.  Zoe has not lived in a house before and will need close supervision until she is trained.  She prefers going on grass and will need a tall securely fenced in backyard.  Before coming to the shelter, Zoe has no exposure to cats and only to other dogs through a fence.  We have been slowly introducing her to other large playful dogs and she has done well.  If you currently own a dog, we can arrange a meet and greet to see if they are compatible.  
Zoe’s first few years haven’t been so great.  Will you help to make sure the rest of her life is spectacular?!  She’s really quite special and we promised to find her a fabulous home.  



To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
ODEN.  This boy once he sniffs you out and decides you are a “keeper”, he will speed wag his tail and give you all the lovins.  When you pet him, he will close his eyes and savor the moment.  Oden loves adult humans, children and dogs.  Oden dislikes ALL cats so there cannot be any cats in the home. 

****More information from Oden's previous owner: Oden will be 1 in February. He is house broken, crate trained. He is great with children, no matter the age. He is great with other dogs, and humans. He just isn’t good with cats, even after trying a year to socialize and change this behavior. He is an inside dog and still in puppy phase. He loves car rides, and walks great on a harness. He is very vocal. He loves playing fetch and running around. Always kept up to date on shots and flea medicine. He is a very good dog.  Oden had a double hematoma in his ears when he was a puppy. This was surgically corrected. If bathing him, it is imperative to make sure no water gets in his ears.*****

Oden is vocal. He will talk / bark at you when you get around his kennel.  Don’t let that put you off - many dogs will do that in a shelter environment.  Get him out in the yard , let him smell the air (& you) and see if you have a love connection with him like I did.  


Oden is sponsored! His adoption fee is $50, fully vetted.  Visitors welcomed Tuesday - Saturday 11AM - 3PM. Appointments not needed, but please bring your masks to wear. Adoption applications available at the shelter after you 've visited and if you've made a love connection. 


*****
If don't have room in your home but do have room in your heart, you can help one of our homeless pets find a home of its own by sponsoring them. By sponsoring, you will be paying part of the adoption fee, making it possible for them to be adopted much sooner. 
            
For Adoption or Sponsorship  Information please call 270-586-3125.  
ADOPTION HOURS:  Tuesday - Saturday 11 am to 3 pm Central Time. Adoption Fee for our dogs is $95.  All dogs will be adopted fully vetted.  Spay/Neuter.  Wormed. animal.description: Hiya! I'm Arielle. Everyone always wants to know how I ended up with WAAL. Well, here's the deal: I had an amazing mom who cared for and loved me a lot! She made sure I had sweaters to keep me warm, lots of toys to play with, a cool cave bed, and lots of blankets. She was wonderful! But, then she started having some health problems and was no longer able to care for me, so she made the VERY difficult decision to let WAAL find me a new forever home . . . one which we know she'd approve of. So, here I am, a loving and trusting girl just looking for a new place to call home. I still have my cave bed, and apparently the way I cuddle in it's pretty funny. That, and how I snore. Yeah . . . I snore a little. Number one thing to know about me? I LOVE being with my people! I am smart, and know "come" and "stay," and am quickly learning about this thing called "crate training;" apparently I'm getting pretty good at it. Other dogs are cool, but I haven't met any of those kitty creatures. They might be cool, too. If you have a loving heart and plenty of time to spend with me ('cause I want to spend lots of time with you), fill out an application so we can meet! ...

animal.description: Hi! My name is Bram! I was rescued by the Palm Beach County Animal Control before being brought to Big Dog Ranch & Rescue. I am a friendly boy and I love to meet new people and play with other dogs. I have medium to high energy and love to run around and play. I would be best in an all-adult home and my opinions on cats are currently unknown. I would be the perfect fit for an experienced dog owner who knows how to harness my energy and size and I can't think of anything that would make me happier than having access to a great big yard to run around and play in. I would be very happy in a busy home with lots going on and I love to get new visitors. I would benefit from some continued training, as I am not quite potty-trained yet and I tend to pull on the leash, but I know that I can get the hang of it in no time!

animal.description:
You'll be writing little hearts beside X's and O's next to Lab/Pit mix Micah name this Valentine's as he is nothing but a hunk of LOVE! He is about 1-2 years old with a stunning fawn coat. He loves riding shotgun and is a good mid-sized pal about 48 lbs, built for more active adventures as well as cuddles on the couch. Overall, Micah is just a happy, friendly guy towards people and dogs alike. He is happy to have landed himself on the farm and is enjoying his time here, but would REALLY love to find a place and people of his very own. To meet Micah, please submit your adoption request at savinggracenc.org

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Duke is a three year old male Boston Terrier. He weighs around 30 lbs. Duke was surrendered to the rescue because he needs to be the only dog in the home. He would probably do best with older kids too. Duke is an absolute bouncy ball of a dog. Keep him busy and he will keep you entertained! Duke is a very happy guy that enjoys meeting new people. He can be adopted by applying at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Tallinn, a 14 lb, 10 week old Lab mix puppy, is an absolute sweetheart. Like many of the dogs rescued from the South he was not a big fan of the cold weather when he first got here. The arrival of the recent snow quickly changed his mind, and he thoroughly enjoyed the strange new experience. Tallinn is a playful and curious puppy, and while he may initially approach new people and situations cautiously, it doesn't take long for him to enthusiastically jump in with all 4 paws. Snuggling and ear rubs are some of his favorite pastimes, and he loves being around people. He is a calm and easy going companion, and will happily accompany his foster family as they go about their daily lives, whether it is doing errands in the car or relaxing on his bed while listening to soothing music. Tallinn is an active little guy, but he also enjoys quietly playing with his toys, fetching a ball or chewing a bone.

Currently weighing in at 14 pounds, we expect Tallinn to grow to about 55-65 pounds. He is doing extremely well with house training and basic obedience and leash skills. He savors his treats and is eager to please, so he should be a highly motivated learner and quickly understand good house manners and appropriate behaviors. Once this little cutie pie finds his way into your life he will captivate your heart, and every day with him will be joyous!


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.
